## State File Schema (~/cockpit/state/ado-tasks.md)

The state file persists across sessions. Only the main cockpit session writes it — agents never touch it.

```markdown
# Sprint State
- Sprint: <name>
- Sprint ID: <guid>
- Last Updated: <ISO timestamp>

## Work Items
| ID | Type | Title | ADO State | Status | Priority | Fitness | Branch | PR | Notes |
|----|------|-------|-----------|--------|----------|---------|--------|----|-------|

## Agent Log
| Timestamp | Item(s) | Action | Details |
|-----------|---------|--------|---------|
```

**Status**: `queued` | `in-progress` | `done` | `blocked` | `skipped`
**Priority**: `P1-livesite` > `P1-active` > `P2-deadline` > `P3`
**Fitness** (agent readiness):
- `ready` — Clear scope, agent can implement autonomously
- `investigate` — Needs root-cause analysis first; agent can research but not fix
- `needs-spec` — Requirements unclear, needs human planning first
- `needs-human` — Requires internal tooling/access an agent can't use
- `batch` — Part of a group; handled with related items
**Agent Log actions**: `agent-started` | `agent-completed` | `agent-failed` | `pr-opened` | `ado-updated` | `status-check`

